README for CAD6.

Our implementation of the program counter follows very similarly to figure 1 included in the handout. We use the same 16 bit 2to1 mux for both jumping and branching. Additionally, we reused the ALU for the adder section, and reused the DFFs from CAD2 to create the actual program counter store. By reusing the components already built for other lab assignments we were able to speed up development, given the tight deadline, though we suffer from clear performance penalties as are illustrated in the large critical path. To implement the three different commands, different combinations of the jump and branch flag are needed. For bcond, when the conditional is met, the displacement value is added to PC by setting the b flag to 1. When conditional is not met, b is set to 0 and the PC is incremented by only 1. In both cases the jump flag is set to 0. For JAL and JCOND, the functionality is mostly the same, except for that in JAL, the jump flag is always 1, while for JCOND the j flag is only set when conditional is met. Additionally, for JAL another flag will be needed to write PC+1 to RLINK register thought this is going to be implemented in the controller. In both JAL and JCOND, the branch flag is set to 0.

Branch targets are calculating by adding whatever value to the current PC value in a new adder which utilizes another instance of the ALU created.

This general configuration for the program counter allows for easy switching of the different 3 instructions based on 3 simple flags which will be set by the controller.

The critical path was when branch is flipped and 1 is added to a PC that is all 1s. This delay was of 4.018 ns, considerably larger than the delay calculated in the adder assignment which was of approximately half a nanosecond. This clearly shows that without optimizing the sizes of the transistors based on the parasitics performance suffers. In particular, the sizes of the transistors in the 16 bit 2 to 1 mux likely could be the most optimized as they drive a large input capacitance in the adder.

PostPEX simulations were not possible for this assignment given the scale of the layout. The extracted PEX is way larger than what xschem can handle which renders these simulations impossible.

Important filses:
schematics/main.sch -> This contains the main logic for the program counter which combines the 16 DFFs, adder, and 16 bit 2 to 1 mux to create the entire PC logic.
main.gds -> Contains the main layout
tbs/jal.sch -> This contains the testbench for the jump and link logic. In particular this shows that PC+1 is the output until the clk edge where this value would be driven into the correct register and at which point PC becomes whatever value was in the register being read. This is shown as the initial output value is 1 as PC=0 until clk edge when PC=21845(what was mocked from register) and thus the output is again PC + 1, so 21846 + 1 as shown in the OUT values included in the waveforms
tbs/jcond.sch -> This contains the jcond instruction which tests for both cases where j is 1 and where j is 0, indicating whether the conditional is met or not. In the case that j=0, we see that we simply pass PC+1. However, when j=1 we set the PC to whatever was stored in the register.
tbs/bcond.sh -> this contains the testbench for the bcond instruction. The two cases, similar to jcond, is when branch is 1 because the conditional is met or branch is 0. In the case that branch is 1, we see clearly that we are adding the value of 3 to the pc which is 1. This is seen clearly in the waveforms illustrated. The input is different from the jump instructions as the value comes from the instruction instead of the RF.
tbs/critical_path_prePEX.sch -> This critical path essentially happens when we must ripple through the 4 bit blocks and occurs when adding 1 to all 1s in the pc, going through the branch.
SUBMIT/spice_critical_path.png -> This shows the 4ns critical path from when Br is toggled and when the final output OUT15 reflects this.
SUBMIT/spice_jal_functionality.png -> This shows the JAL functionality. In particular it shows how before the CLK edge we have PC+1 at the output for the RF and after the input of 01010101... is passed to the PC
SUBMIT/spice_jcond_functionality.png -> This shows the two different possibilities for jumping. At the first CLK edge j is not set and we simply add 1 to pc, however during the second clk edge J flag is set which means the 01010101... value is passed to PC as refleced in the outputs presented in the waveform.
SUBMIT/spice_bcond_D0_D1_high.png -> This waveform shows though unclearly that D0 and D1 are high while the rest are set to 0. This is important because this value of 3 is added to the PC, which is shown in the output as soon as the positive clk edge is hit. This is shown clearly in the next waveform:
SUBMIT/spice_bcond_CLK_Br_and_OUTs.png -> This waveform shows the switching of the output to be the sign extended disp, though the output still shows PC + disp until branch flag is turned off in which case we see PC + 1 or disp + 1 = 100 which is expected and we see clearly that only OUT2 is high after this in the waveform.
